^-|FP||cp||ht|d|AT|^B@2We need the following definitions to better understand what are outlined in this synopsis.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

As responder after a 1NT opener, your hands fall into one of 3 categories--|CP|8|FP|2|AT|MINIMUM, MEDIUM,|cp||at| or |cp|8|at|MAXIMUM. |FP||CP||AT|The point ranges are slightly different than the ranges we discussed earlier. The point ranges are:|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


CP|8|FP|2|AT|

  ^cMinimum |FP||CP||AT|^f- no more than 7 points; game is not possible;|CP|8|FP|2|AT|
  ^CMedium |FP||CP||AT|^f- 8-9 points; game is possible if opener has a maximum NT (defined below);|CP|8|FP|2|AT|
  ^CMaximum |FP||CP||AT|^f- 10 or more points; you must bid game.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|
    
Strong NT hands also fall into one of 2 categories |CP|8|FP|2|AT|MAXIMUM|cp||at| or |CP|8|FP|2|AT| MINIMUM|FP||CP||AT|.
A NT hand is considered a MAXIMUM if it meets any of the following criteria:|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

^C* Any hand with 17 HCP
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP and a fit with responder's major suit
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP and a 5-card suit
^C* Any hand with 16 HCP, not 4-3-3-3 distribution, and at least two 10s or 9s.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

A NT hand is considered a MINIMUM if it does not meet any of the above criteria.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|


